April 4 1948
Dear Jack.
I was certainly sorry to miss adding my dulcet voice to your "Happy Birthday." Somehow there seems to be interference whenever I am invited to one of your special gatherings. Next time I am really going to be SORE!
Helen tells me "you librarian" should go to the {devine} library and see Miss Nancy Scott. There is a likely possibility for a summer job on the campus. Helen is in the periodical room and if he goes, he should stop in and say hello to her.
Why can't Sam and Mrs. Conroy and I have dinner
Completed

together some night? At least we can talk between bites.
I can't resist quoting a tid bit from the New Yorker I read today.
"The nation steams like a cup of hot coffee, and the patriot's spectacles become fogged, so that he sees nothing except through the mind's eye, merely feels the strong, warm liquid going into his stomach, stimulating his glands." There are indeed our patriots!
I hope you can arrange some suitable time with
Completed

Dear Jack:
Just a small donation for you or unclear: amy & your friends.
Yesterday, I saw [unclear]]" at Donnelly's. A sad fate when names speaks!
My best to mrs. Conroy and the boys.
Sophia

November 22, 1948
Dear Jack,
I take my pen in hand only to tell you the bad news. 
We could not stop publication of the Count-Schuman version of my book because I did not loan the money to put down.  It required a bond, not less than then thousand dollars (of they accepted such a small challenge) to serve an injunction and stop publication of the book.  The New York attorney I am told was heart broken because he said we had a 100-1 scoop. 
Strangely enough it just has dawned on me that undoubtedly this new version must be written by the fellow that was to put the Count-Prior version in such fine form.  You may have heard of him, Malcolm Brinnin -- and he a good friend of the Bergan Evans family.  This (the above) is my guess so don't quote me.  Count cannot write a straight sentence.
Completed

2.
But, my reason for being really sore is that he, Brinnan, wrote to Harpers Bazaar and wanted the illustrations for my book to be published in the magazine -- in the December issue.  Terrible mix up is what I got into.
That isn't all though.  I fell at our Institute and really hurt myself.  I broke a third rib and almost lost the use of my RIGHT arm.  How would you like to wring the neck of the black unclear that's following me around. 
I am serious about getting together sometime for an evening of Conroyisms.  A life of all mice and no men digs a deep rut.
My best to Mrs. Conroy and the boys.
Sophia

Sunday June 19th
Dear Jack
When the invitation to the conference on American Folklore for Children arrived, I realized how long its been since I had your letter. The connection of course lies in Elizabeth Pilants explanation that I was invited at your suggestion.
Even if I had any contribution to make to this conference I still would be unable to attend. No matter how much thought I give to the subject, I have yet been unable to devise any scheme whereby I could quit working and continue to exist and so that most essential part of my time work prevents my being at that conference. I do get a vacation but choice of time is on a seniority basis. And so I get my vacation in Sept. and plan to go to Chicago as would enjoy seeing them again more than exploring new places. Besides I was in Texas and New Orleans with a short jaunt to Monterey, Mexico and another short trim along the Gulf of Mexico boarding Mississippi last winter when I went to school for a short training course. That should been the needs of new
Completed

place to be seen for one year.
As to those children's stories I collect, everyone seems to like them. As you know aside from the experience with one agent, I sent them to one publishers namely Doubleday. After holding these for about 7 weeks they finally sent an acknowledgement saying they required still more time to give the stories adequate consideration.
I gathers they were holding them to discuss along with other manuscripts for consideration when compiling their next season list. They kept the stories still another month and then returned them with this statement. "We have read children's stores for adults and regret that after careful consideration we are unable to fit it into our list." etc.
In a way I can see their point. They do need assurance that books they publicize as coming out will be ready and since these stories depend on my finding articulate children, in addition to recognizing a good one when I hear it, they can't be guaranteed for any date deadline. I'm sure they would bring in as great financial returns to a publisher as the usual children's stories, and more, as they would have an adult market as well as  one for children.
So I guess the thing for me to do is concentrate on getting more of these before tying up my time with one publisher after another or to send those I have to a magazine. You might suggest which would be interested in the stories I have?
